data.body:
The goal of #14803 is that you should be able to write this:

```js
import { PerspectiveCamera } from 'three';
import { OrbitControls } from 'three/examples/js/controls/OrbitControls';
```

I'm hopeful that will provide a better situation for all of the examples... there are open questions still on how to manage the transition, though: https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/pull/14803#issuecomment-420741932

@donmccurdy  If you import it using
```javascript
import { OrbitControls } from 'three/examples/js/controls/OrbitControls';
```
can you still import it without importing the whole library? I'm just trying to keep my bundle as small as possible by only using what I need. I guess I don't know enough about this whole project to know how the global THREE gets used, but it seems to me with that implementation you'd need to import all the modules twice if you used them elsewhere.

for example, if you had something like 
```javascript
import { PerspectiveCamera, Spherical } from 'three';
import { OrbitControls } from 'three/examples/js/controls/OrbitControls';
```

Your bundle would now have Spherical imported from the math/Spherical.js module, and the definition of THREE.Spherical() imported for the global object.

Also, you now have a syntax that requires knowledge of the whole libraries file structure in order to use those components. It's not bad for an interim step, but in the end it's hard to get started with a library where you have to jump through a lot of hoops and use inconsistent import schemes to get at various components. Also, once it's set up like that people are going to start depending on it which will make it very difficult to change.

@WestLangley can't people just copy out the logic out of the source and roll their own implementation if they want to change the way it works?

@donmccurdy I get your point, and I've seen other libraries do that successfully, but it does add a layer of complexity to the developer. For example, there are some animations and geometries in the examples folder, would those be in new npm modules? How do you know when to get an animation from the core library and when to reference the external module? How do you even decide which goes where? It seems like the easiest thing is just to port them all to the core library on request.

I do think you raise some valid points about users not using ES modules yet, or thier build systems not supporting tree-shaking. That being said, lots of new developers are coming to JS with create-react-app in hand and other boilerplates that set this all up for them, and I believe the trend will continue to move toward good support for ES modules.

### suggests:
install
```shell
npm install @threejs/core @threejs/orbit-control
```

use
```js
import THREE from '@threejs/core';
import OrbitControls from '@threejs/orbit-control';

const controls = new OrbitControls(camera);
```

and org [@threejs](https://www.npmjs.com/org/threejs) available.

@mrdoob @donmccurdy see see

> (3) In the future, it will not matter what is bundled in the core/build since the practice of bundling is slowly but surely becoming unnecessary.

@arodic I think there are a few exceptions to this rule, but I agree with your other points.

I'm closing this issue, but we'll keep working on these issues — making sure the whole library isn't imported, especially — in #14803 and future PRs.

@sanonz

> and org @threejs available.

I just created the org 😊

